A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Space Systems Command is executing Space Systems Prototype Transition (SSPT) (Project 645601) for Guardians across Space Control, Space Access, Networks,
Command and Control, Warfighting, and the Space Domain Awareness Enterprise. As a result, the Service will deter, neutralize, defeat and/or destroy counterspace
threats and defend the homeland, principled public servants; space-minded warfighters; and bold and collaborative problem solvers.

 The Space Systems Prototype Transitions Program addresses space technology and capability gaps to facilitate technology transition of military space prototypes into
 programs of record. SSPT conducts an array of activities to model, integrate, test, provide launch integration for, and support on-orbit testing of prototype technologies.
 The supported activities include systems engineering, technology planning, development, demonstration and testing, as well as modeling, simulation, and exercises to
 support the development and maturation of tactics, techniques, and procedures. This includes developing and prototyping critical technology within the Department of
 War, other government agencies, academia, and industry partners, along with the necessary systems engineering for effective deployment.

 Project 645601, Space Defense Capabilities, prototypes technologies and facilitates informed insertion to programs of record and provides platforms to operate
 prototypes in space. Project 645611, Assault Breaker II, is an all-Service, classified, multi-year effort, led by the Office of the Under Secretary of War for Research and
 Engineering (OUSW(R&E)) to analyze, research, and recommend material and non-material solutions to the Joint Requirements Oversight Council/Requirements and
 Resourcing Alignment Board.

 This program falls within the Science and Technology (S&T) and Test & Evaluation (T&E) mission area which provides the S&T initiatives, demonstrations, experiments,
 and studies towards developing next-generation space capabilities. The T&E mission area provides all efforts required to establish and operate the test infrastructure for
 USSF capabilities. Program interdependencies include:
 Defense Research Sciences (0601102SF); Major T&E Investments - Space (1206759SF); Small Business Innovation Research (1205502SF); Space Advanced
 Tech Dev / Demo (1206616SF); Space Innov Intg & Rapid Tech Dev (1203174SF); Space Rapid Capabilities Office (1206857SF); Space Science and Technology
 (1206310SF); Space Technology (1206601SF); Space Test and Evaluation (1202051SF); Space Test Program (1206864SF); University Research Initiatives
 (0601103SF).

 The SSPT Program establishes a cost-effective framework to identify, mature and transition demonstrations and prototypes to:

