A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The Space Defense Capabilities project prototypes technologies for insertion into programs of record and provides platforms to operate prototypes in space.

 The Rapid On-Orbit Space Technology Evaluation Ring (ROOSTER) provides a low-cost, rapid, and flexible on-orbit capability to host and deploy numerous prototypes
 and payloads in order to mature critical technologies and enable investment or divestment decisions. Each ROOSTER on-orbit platform is designed to fly multiple
 payloads per mission, thus fully utilizing launch potential and providing the only recurring rideshare option for prototypes, demonstrations, and experiments to
 geosynchronous orbit. The objectives of the ROOSTER program are to enable rapid and cost-effective technology insertion into operational programs of record through
 the on-orbit checkout and testing of prototypes, demonstrations, and experimental payloads. Additionally, ROOSTER will work to mature operational concepts and
 tactics, techniques, and procedures, such as on-obit refueling, for use within the United States Space Force space enterprise architecture.

 Tetra provides a pathfinder to define future system architectures and operational concepts for several Space Domain Awareness (SDA) and Space Control programs
 and other mission partners, as well as prove prototype and experiment technologies for the Air Force Research Laboratory (AFRL) and other Department of War labs.
 It serves as an additional platform to host prototype and experiment payloads that need to operate in concert with ROOSTERs. As a secondary mission, it provides a
 training platform for operators to develop and demonstrate tactics, techniques, and procedures for the evolution of operations and training in alignment with objectives
 from organizations such as the National Space Test and Training Complex and United States Space Force Space Training and Readiness Command.

 Quasi-Zenith Satellite System-Hosted Payload has dual goals of enhancing the US-Japan alliance and proving the feasibility and capability of a SDA sensor payload
 able to be proliferated and hosted on US and non-US satellites. In addition to prototyping such a capability, it will serve as a dedicated sensor in the Space Surveillance
 Network, enhancing SDA in Geostationary Earth Orbit over the Eurasian theater.

 Space-to-Space Communications includes development of communications technologies to synchronize space-to-space Command and Control and data transport
 needs across the space community and enable system-agnostic communication pathways via a mobile ad-hoc network. It enhances the Defense Advanced Research
 Projects Agency Space-Based Adaptive Communication Node modem design to support long-range crosslinks and incorporate emerging optical waveform standards. In
 cooperation with AFRL, it develops networking systems to manage the Space Data Network (SDN). It also develops and maintains a communications testbed to mature
 communication waveforms and validate hardware.

 This program element may include necessary civilian pay expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver Space Systems Prototype Transitions capability. The use
 of such program funds would be in addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 1206392SF and 1206398SF.


