D. Acquisition Strategy
All contracts funded in this program element will be awarded using competitive procedures to the maximum extent possible. The Space Systems Prototype Transitions
(SSPT) program consists of numerous projects in which the program office will leverage rapid prototyping authorities to the maximum extent possible.

 The Rapid On-Orbit Space Technology Evaluation Ring (ROOSTER) acquisition strategy was approved in 2Q FY 2022. A sole-source contract was awarded for
 ROOSTER 2Q FY 2023 which supports the ROOSTER-4 Initial Launch Capability (ILC) 1Q FY 2027. The follow-on ROOSTER-5 bus contract was competitively
 awarded in 1Q FY 2025 through a mission partner's contract. The payload and launch vehicle integration, ground systems development, and operation support scope
 will be awarded via sole-source contract to the bus contractor in 4Q FY 2025. The ROOSTER-6 bus contract will be competitively awarded in 1Q FY 2026 through a
 mission partner's contract. The payload and launch vehicle integration, ground systems development, and the operations scope will be awarded again via sole source to
 the bus contractor in late FY 2026 with an intent to simplify interfaces and reduce integration costs.

 The Tetra program office maintains the flexibility to employ a different acquisition strategy to procure, develop, and launch each Tetra. The first two Tetra vehicles were
 procured simultaneously as the first award on the Space Enterprise Consortium (SpEC) Other Transaction Authority (OTA) agreement. Tetras 3 and 4 were awarded in
 4Q 2019. Tetra-5a awarded in 4Q 2022. Air Force Research Lab Tetra-5c has now been re-purposed to fulfill the Tetra 6 mission which was awarded in 3Q FY 2024.

 The Quasi-Zenith Satellite System—Hosted Payload acquisition strategy is to procure the two prototype payloads from Massachusetts Institute of Technology Lincoln
 Laboratory through a sole-source contract to develop and test the pathfinding system, as well as provide integration and long-term factory support. After the payloads'
 prototype mission, they will transition to an operational leave-behind mission, serving as dedicated sensors to Space Surveillance Network. Lessons learned in system
 development on-orbit operations will inform requirements and accelerate design for follow-on systems, as well as inform Space Domain Awareness Force Design and
 architecture.

 The S2S Comms acquisition strategy awarded agreements to multiple developers to develop beyond Low Earth Orbit optical crosslink terminal prototypes. These
 awards occurred on the SpEC OTA vehicle using a three-phased approach with potential down-selects occurring after Phase 1 and/or Phase 2. The total period of
 performance is planned for 34 months. In parallel, the project will fund further development of a low size, weight, and power optical modem developed under the

