across warfighting, operations commands, combat support, and combat service support units. As a result, the Service will improve battle management of all weapon
systems; deliver space domain awareness capabilities; improve readiness and operational reach of existing force structure; deter, neutralize, defeat and/or destroy
counterspace threats and defend the homeland; augment, supplement, and/or integrate Allies, partners, and commercial space to USSF units; continue to advance all
near term effects; and achieve resilient infrastructure, equipment, and personnel.

 This program falls within the Satellite Communications (SATCOM) mission area which provides the space and dedicated ground architecture required to securely
 transport wideband, narrowband, tactical, and strategic satellite communications, including USSF-funded SATCOM terminals and commercial SATCOM activities.
 Space Force investment program interdependencies include: RDT&E Budget Line Items: Advanced EHF MILSATCOM (1206431SF); Commercial SATCOM Integration
 (1206445SF); Evolved Strategic SATCOM (ESS) (1206855SF); Family of Adv BLoS Terminals (FAB-T) (1203001SF); Narrowband Satellite Communications
 (1203109SF); Protected Tactical Enterprise Service (1206760SF); Protected Tactical Service (1206761SF; Space Tech Development & Prototyping (1206410SF);
 Tech Transition (Space) (1206458SF); Wideband Global SATCOM (SPACE) (1206433SF); Space Data Network (1203636SF); and elements of Procurement Budget
 Line Items: Family of Beyond Line-of-Sight Terminals (FBLOST); Mobile User Objective System (MUOS00); MILSATCOM (MILSAT); Wideband SATCOM Operational
 Management Systems (WSOMS0); Auxiliary Payloads (AUX000); Proliferated Low Earth Orbit SATCOM (PLEO00); PTES HUB (PTES00); and ESS (ESS000).

 In FY 2027, the USSF transferred the following projects into PE 1203156SF (Data Transport and Networking) in order to consolidate the management and execution of
 similar enterprise solutions. This is not a new start. PE 1203940SF (Space Situation Awareness Operations) Project 673941 (Unified Data Library) effort transferred to
 Project 673941 (Unified Data Library). PE 1203310SF (Satellite Control Network (SPACE), Project 673276 (Satellite Control Network major thrust MeshONE-T (M1T)
 effort transferred to Project 673944 (MeshONE-T (M1T)). PE 1203010SF (Space Force IT, Data Analytics, Digital Solutions) Project 646602 (Integrated Operation
 Networking) effort transferred to Project 673945 (Integrated Operations Networking).

 The distinct data service projects in this PE -- UDL, M1T, and ION -- serve as the enterprise backbone solutions to the USSF's system of systems data and networking
 architecture. Each project plays a part in the global mission data ecosystem from data networking to data distribution to machine-to-machine solutions to modernize
 currently fielded systems, support incorporation of new systems, or improve data access and security through cloud-based and hybrid environments.
Operational Systems Development

 This system of systems guarantees the flow of trusted, battle-ready data from any sensor to any warfighter by way of connectivity, transport, and data federation The
 Data Transport and Networking (DTN) program operationalizes data as a decisive weapon system for USSF, fusing critical infrastructure into combat capabilities.
 To meet mission effects, data must be available, discoverable, and trusted. Data transport is a critical function to make data available between space sensors, major
 operation centers, and Guardians at the tactical edge—even in contested, degraded, and operationally limited environments where options to move data are paramount.
 A continuity of solutions shared across the enterprise backbone drives efficient approaches to how DTN leverages its resources to meet mission requirements. The
 DTN will focus on developing more scalable, machine-to-machine advancements that enable further modernization of currently fielded weapon systems, incorporating
 them into the meshed network and federated data solutions. Use of secure, cloud-based environments enables seamless data transfer across all classification levels,
 facilitating enhanced collaboration and decision-making for warfighting units.

 This program element may include necessary civilian pay expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver weapon system capability. The use of such program funds
 would be in addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 1206392SF and 1206398SF.

 This program is in Budget Activity 7, Operational System Development because this budget activity includes development efforts to upgrade systems that have been
 fielded or have received approval for full rate production and anticipate production funding in the current or subsequent fiscal year.$$, $$This is not a New Start. In FY 2027, funds for Integrated Operations Networking (ION) are transferred from PE 1203010SF, Project 646602 to PE 1203156SF, Project
673945.

 The USSF's Integrated Operations Networking (ION) effort is a critical component of the Space Force's mission to enable the Battle Management, Command, Control,
 and Communications (BMC3) warfighter missions. ION will integrate commercially available information technology (IT) capabilities to address urgent operational
 needs and close networking gaps tied to kill chain gaps identified by Space Forces - Space operating in support of USSPACECOM. ION aims to improve tactical and
 operational timelines within the kill-chain to enable USSF's ability to deliver credible combat power effects in support of the Joint Force.

 The program will focus on developing a secure, reliable, and multi-classification transport layer to support space missions, with an emphasis on direct connection
 between all elements of force packages, establishing a special access program (SAP)-level network with overlays, and developing high-speed connectivity and high
 resilience to Commercial Cloud Services (C2S). The ION program will also pursue opportunities to leverage existing efforts, such as meshONE-T, to support the
 development of ION.

 Funding in FY 2027 will enable the program to maintain a steady pace of execution throughout the year, ensuring that the Space Force can leverage the ION capability
 to enhance its mission effectiveness. The ION program will provide a critical capability to the Space Force, enabling the service to operate in a contested environment
 and to defend against adversary operations. The program will be executed in a manner that is consistent with the Space Force's priorities, including the development of
 a digital engineering ecosystem, the implementation of zero trust capabilities, and the modernization of cryptography and supply chain risk management.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                      FY 2025           FY 2026    FY 2027
Title: USSF Integrated Operations Networking (ION)                                                                                              -                 -      34.822
Description: ION will provide a secure, reliable, multi-classification transport layer to support space missions. ION will be a
dynamic cloud-based software-defined mission networking gap filler that integrates Space Force capabilities providing high
bandwidth and low latency for essential capabilities including support to Artificial Intelligence (AI) and the Unified Data Library
(UDL). Space Force initiated ION to address significant mission network infrastructure technology debt and to better prepare for
a new threat environment. ION will continue to deploy a special and compartmented access program (SAP/CAP) capable Unified
Data Library within an accredited government cloud that will enable mission partners to access timely, high resolution data at all

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                      FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
classification levels. The expansion of cloud infrastructure and resilient movement of data are solutions to gaps in USSPACECOM
Offensive Counter Space, Defensive Counter-Space and Integrated Fires Capabilities.

FY 2027 Plans:
FY 2027 efforts will focus on scaling and accelerating the expansion of classified cloud and networking infrastructure to
support secure data transport in alignment with projected threat timelines. This includes building upon the existing pathfinder
implementation to connect disparate classified space capabilities into integrated, resilient data transport network. ION will
continue to support the terrestrial network, advancing the integration of a secure, reliable, multi-classification transport layer.
This includes the incorporation of Command and Control (C2) nodes into the existing classified kill web, directly enhancing the
National Space Test and Training Complex (NSTTC). These improvements will increase classified communication resiliency, align
development activities, and expand opportunities for advanced training and testing- leveraging test and training data sources into
UDL to strengthen USSF's ability to protect and defend high-priority space missions. ION enables rapid response capabilities by
enhancing system resiliency and situational awareness—key to operating in a contested space domain. Planned activities may
include, but are not limited to program office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation, risk reduction, and prototyping.
Efforts may leverage commercial, U.S. Government partnership, and international opportunities to respond to existing and
emerging adversarial threats with speed and agility.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2027 funding increased due to ION funds transferring into this new Program Element 1203156SF, Project 673945 in FY 2027
to consolidate data transport and networking efforts to provide greater transparency and alignment of common functions. This is
not a new start.
