A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
This is not a new start. In FY 2027, Cyber Secure Mission Data Transport, known as meshONE-Terrestrial or meshONE-T, efforts were transferred from PE 1203110SF,
Satellite Control Network (SPACE), Project 673276, to PE 1203156SF, Data Transport & Networking, Project 673944, meshONE-T, in order to consolidate data
transport and networking efforts to provide greater transparency and alignment of common functions.

 The meshONE-T (M1T) system provides an enterprise networking capability for USSF and other customers through proliferation of nodes utilizing diversified long-
 haul communication circuits to provide high speed, scalable, resilient, cyber-secure transport services for mission data producers and consumers. These services
 are operated and managed via Enterprise Service Desk (ESD) / Network Operation Center (NOC) sites. The multi-tenant, mission-agnostic system uses Commercial
 Off The Shelf (COTS)-based solutions and industry standard protocols to move data traffic quickly, efficiently, and securely across the Internet Protocol (IP)-based
 network architecture. M1T meets the needs of the Combatant Commands—with specific focus on USINDOPACOM and USEUCOM. Modern mission data transport
 services will support Next-Gen and Future Operationally Resilient Ground Evolution (FORGE) Overhead Persistent Infrared (OPIR), Advanced Battle Management
 System (ABMS), Missile Track Custody (MTC), Space Domain Awareness (SDA), SCN, USSF Integrated Operations Networking (ION), Launch and Test Range System
 (LTRS), and other mission partners. Supplementary/backup NOCs, communication links, bandwidth upgrades, and system improvements increase global operational
 reach, resiliency, and responsiveness to support warfighter operations through all phases of conflict. Software defined networking capabilities accelerate onboarding of
 new mission partners and the delivery of transport services, providing the agility necessary to counter emerging threats. M1T resolves current space mission network
 shortfalls including antiquated protocols, bandwidth constraints, lack of resiliency, cyber vulnerability, and excessive fielding times. All mission partners using M1T will
 become part of the USSF ground network enterprise, with access to every node and network-provided cyber-secure services.

 Other activities include identifying shared/common platform, infrastructure and data layer solutions to support open frameworks and architectures across the enterprise
 ground portfolio. Funds are also used for requirements management, system planning, enterprise analysis and architecture support, Systems Engineering and
 Integration (SE&I), cyber security, test, system enhancement and deficiency resolution, and system resiliency.

