Development

Note
This Program Element (PE)/ Project was established in FY 2021 for the development of the SSN(X) Class Submarine.

FY 2026 funding levels increased from PB25 levels to achieve SSN(X) Lead Ship Authorization as early as FY 2040. FY 2026 efforts will be informed by the Analysis
of Alternatives (AoA) results to build design base readiness, initial Capability Development Document (CDD) preparation, design refinement based on mission
effectiveness differentiators, and completing Gate 2.

A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The U.S. Navy must protect the security of the American people by defending against great powers, regional adversaries, and transnational threats. Near peer
adversaries are increasing the demand on the U.S. Navy submarine force. The 2025 Interim National Defense Strategy directs the DoD to deter aggression by China in
the Indo-Pacific reiterating the need for attack submarines in the pacing scenario. The U.S. Navy must meet the rising challenge by delivering a new attack submarine.
SSN(X) will significantly contribute to rebuilding our military, reinforcing deterrence in the undersea, and building lethality in the Joint Force. It will provide greater speed,
increased horizontal payload capacity, improved signatures, higher operational availability, and flexibility to adapt to uncertain future threats. SSN(X) will conduct full
spectrum undersea warfare and employ and coordinate with a larger contingent of off-hull remote autonomous systems (RAS) and sensors as a force multiplier. It will
retain and improve multi-mission (Anti-Surface Warfare (ASuW), Anti-Submarine Warfare (ASW), Subsea Seabed Warfare (SSW), Strike, Special Operating Forces
(SOF), Mine, and Intelligence, Surveillance and Reconnaissance (ISR)) capability and sustained combat presence in denied waters. SSN(X) will operate independently
or be integrated within a Task Force.

The formal acquisition strategy for SSN(X) is being developed and will be informed by requirements post the Analysis of Alternatives (AoA). Preliminary Design for
SSN(X) will be accomplished through a collaborative Navy-Industry effort to maximize the benefits of industry and the potential shipbuilders. The SSN(X) program
initiated the AoA in FY 2024 to determine the preferred capability solution. The approved Material Development Decision (MDD) designated the SSN(X) a pre-Major
Defense Acquisition Program (MDAP), Acquistion Category (ACAT) IB in FY 2025. PB26 provides the required technology development efforts and ramp to support
Lead Ship Authorization as early as 2040.

FY 2025 focused on technology development efforts started in FY 2024 and completion of the AoA. The SSN(X) program completed the Digital Engineering Strategy to
establish the tailored implementation of digital engineering practices across the acquisition life cycle. The SSN(X) program aligns with the Virginia Class Block VIII efforts
to support maintaining the design base for SSN(X) as well as provide risk reduction for technology development.



