B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions, Article Quantities in Each)                                                             FY 2027    FY 2027     FY 2027
                                                                                                                       FY 2025   FY 2026     Base       OOC         Total
* Deep Sea Expeditionary No "D" (DSEND) Suit: Continue development and start testing of a 600 fsw suit. This
will allow Navy divers to work at significant depths in a self-propelled, flexible suit without the need to perform
lengthy decompression or be at risk for decompression sickness.
* Prehensor Development: Develop prehensors for arm appendages of DSEND suit to improve diver ability to
grab and hold. Development to emphacize better ergonimics and human factors design. These prehensors will
reduce diver fatigue and allow for better use of diver bottom time.
* DiveEar Noise Cancellation: Develop noise cancellation technology for DiveEar ear pieces. This technology
will reduce background noise for diver quieting the overall noise environment for the diver and allowing clearer
understanding of communications from topside.
* Cooling Suit Development & Testing: Continue development and testing of cooling suits for use by divers
in contaminated water applications. The suit will serve to keep divers at a comfortable temperature while
performing heavy work in a sealed contaminated water suit. Use of this suit will markedly improve the divers
ability to perform work while keeping them safe from contaminated water and markedly improve their safety from
heat-related maladies.
* ANU Item Testing / Retesting: Testing of life support and other underwater systems for inclusion on the ANU
list. This will include both testing of existing ANU items to ensure continued compliance with configuration
management and quality or the testing of new items that are desired by fleet divers.
FY 2027 Base Plans:
* Deep Sea Expeditionary No "D" (DSEND) Suit: Continue development and start testing of a 600 fsw suit. This
will allow Navy divers to work at significant depths in a self-propelled, flexible suit without the need to perform
lengthy decompression or be at risk for decompression sickness.
* Authorized Navy Use (ANU) Item Testing / Retesting: Testing of life support and other underwater systems for
inclusion on the ANU list. This will include both testing of existing ANU items to ensure continued compliance
with configuration management and quality or the testing of new items that are desired by fleet divers.
* Prehensor Development: Develop prehensors for arm appendages of DSEND suit to improve diver ability to
grab and hold. Development to emphacize better ergonimics and human factors design. These prehensors will
reduce diver fatigue and allow for better use of diver bottom time.
* DiveEar Noise Cancellation: Develop noise cancellation technology for DiveEar ear pieces. This technology
will reduce background noise for diver quieting the overall noise environment for the diver and allowing clearer
understanding of communications from topside.
