B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions, Article Quantities in Each)                                                           FY 2027    FY 2027      FY 2027
                                                                                                                      FY 2025   FY 2026    Base       OOC          Total
Description: Diver Health and Safety Research: Novel methods for decompression safety and treatment of
decompression sickness/arterial gas embolism. Advanced decompression models for extreme environments,
including thermally challenging, long duration, multi-gas, and/or diving at altitude. Diving physiology advances
in exercise, thermal exposure, oxygen/carbon dioxide alterations, other gas mixture alternations, hydration,
and sustained operations. Develop pulmonary oxygen toxicity exposure limits. Provide pulmonary and Central
Nervous System (CNS) oxygen toxicity mitigation strategies. Develop an advanced diver thermal model.
Develop advanced insulation garments for diver thermal protection. Develop guidance for optimizing thermal
control during decompression. Develop guidelines for conduct of diving operations at altitude. Develop guidance
for infra- and ultra-sound diver exposure. Continue collection of operational and research dive data for inclusion
in advanced probabilistic decompression models. Investigate diver in-water maladies. Develop/improve real-time
decompression guidance and dive planning. Research procedures for assessing and mitigating risk for diving in
contaminated water.

FY 2026 Plans:
*Multi-year project (ending in FY27) addressing contaminated water including a foreign port prediction tool to
assist operational units in predicted contamination levels and informing operational protective posture.

* Continuing evaluation of commercially available free-swimming cooling suit solution to address thermal strain in
contaminated water.

*Real-time diving decompression control utilizing venous gas emboli project will be completed in FY26.

*Underwater noise dosimetry (ending in FY27) - Characterize the capabilities of underwater diver worn monitors
to measure the types and levels of sounds divers are exposed to in active operational environments, 2)
investigate the relationship between the noise exposure dose and auditory changes measured before and after
the dives, and 3) compare measurements to currently established guidelines (permissible exposure limits).

*Skin infiltration model (Ending in FY 28) (2 models) - Dermal exposure limits for waterborne contaminants are
currently unknown and limit effective pre-dive planning. The purpose of these projects is to inform exposure
limits for waterborne contaminants and build a knowledge base for use in pre-dive planning.




