Description: Research, development, testing, design, procurement, and installation of technologies to support
improvements, increase resiliency, and enhance capabilities of equipment, processes, and procedures required
to ensure successful escape and rescue of Distressed Submarine (DISSUB) survivors, sustaining system
effectiveness through its operational lifecycle, including development of the next generation Submarine Rescue
System (SRS). The ability to ensure successful escape and rescue is a core function of the Undersea Warfare
enterprise.

FY 2026 Plans:
Continue execution of critical technologies necessary to sustain the Navy's only submarine rescue capability
through its end of life and prevent inoperability. The SRS Modernization program is essential to meet mission
requirements. It addresses numerous subsystems and components with known capability gaps, obsolescence,
unsustainable maintenance costs, and unacceptable risks. The program proactively resolves system deficiencies
and upgrades many system subcomponents within a System-of-Systems approach to ensure adequate
technology margins are, and will remain, available. Planned upgrades include, but are not limited to, Micro-
electronics System Upgrades, Active Motion Heave Compensation, and Through-hull communications to provide
an end-to-end Distressed Submarine (DISSUB) communications system that enhances capabilities by enabling
rescue from an unresponsive submarine.
FY 2027 Base Plans:
